COMMON FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS COMMON FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”), is entered into as of September 12, 2016 (the “Effective Date”), by and between FPL Energy Wyman LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Wyman”) and FPL Energy Wyman IV LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Wyman IV”, and together with Wyman, the “Parties” or the “Fossil Station Owners” and each individually a “Party”). RECITALS WHEREAS, Wyman and Wyman IV are affiliated subsidiaries of NextEra Energy Resources, LLC; WHEREAS, Wyman owns and operates Units 1, 2, and 3 of an existing fossil generation facility located in Yarmouth, Maine with an aggregate nameplate capacity of 223 MW (the “Wyman Station”) and Wyman IV is the majority owner and operator of the fossil generation plant also located in Yarmouth, Maine with a nameplate capacity of 614.5 MW known as William F. Wyman Unit No. 4 (the “Wyman IV Station”, together with the Wyman Station, the “Fossil Stations” and each a “Fossil Station”); WHEREAS, Wyman is developing and will own and operate a battery energy storage facility with a nameplate capacity of 16.2 MW located on the same property in Yarmouth, Maine as the Fossil Stations (the “Storage Project”, together with the Fossil Stations, the “Projects” and each a “Project”); WHEREAS, Wyman and Central Maine Power Company (“CMP”) are parties to that certain Continuing Site/Interconnection Agreements, effective as of April 14, 2015 (the “CMP-Wyman CSIA”), which generally defines the operational procedures, access rights, maintenance duties and other rights and obligations regarding the interconnection of Wyman Station to the CMP transmission and distribution system; WHEREAS, Wyman IV and CMP are parties to that certain Continuing Site/Interconnection Agreements, effective as of April 14, 2015 (the “CMP-Wyman IV CSIA”, together with the CMP-Wyman CSIA, the “CSIAs”), which generally defines the operational procedures, access rights, maintenance duties and other rights and obligations regarding the interconnection of Wyman IV Station to the CMP transmission and distribution system;
WHEREAS, shortly after execution of this Agreement, Wyman intends to enter into a three-party Small Generation Interconnection Agreement (“SGIA”) with the New England Independent System Operator (“ISO-NE”) and CMP (the “Storage SGIA”);
WHEREAS, Storage Project being developed by Wyman will rely on certain equipment as described in Exhibit A attached hereto, which are currently owned/used by the Fossil Stations in accordance with legacy provisions in that certain Joint Ownership Agreement (“Joint Ownership Agreement”), dated November 1, 1974, for the Wyman IV Fossil Station and which are necessary to interconnect the Storage Project to the CMP transmission facilities operated by the ISO-NE (the “Common Facilities”); WHEREAS, Wyman and Wyman IV are entering into this Common Facilities Agreement to allow the Storage Project being developed by Wyman to use the Common Facilities and to enable Wyman and the Storage Project to inject the energy output of the Storage Project into the electric transmission system of CMP as operated by the ISO-NE, both before and after Wyman executes the Storage SGIA; NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows: AGREEMENT TERM; EARLY TERMINATION Term. Subject to Section 1.2 below, the term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect for twelve (12) years from the Effective Date. As long as the Storage Project is in operation, the term of this Agreement may be extended by mutual agreement of the Parties. Early Termination. This Agreement shall automatically terminate, without further action by any Party and without further liability of any Party to any other Party (except for obligations accruing prior to the termination), upon the date that the Fossil Station Owners or Wyman on behalf of the Storage Project, or their successors and assigns, shall have permanently ceased operation of the Fossil Stations for the production of electric energy and the Storage Project for the charging and discharging of electric energy. GRANT OF COMMON FACILITIES RIGHTS Grant. During the Term of this Agreement, the Fossil Station Owners hereby grant to Wyman’s Storage Project, on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof including but not limited to payment by Wyman of the Storage Projects of its share of Common O&M Expenses and any Storage O&M Expenses pursuant to Section 4.1, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Common Facilities as may be reasonably necessary for the ownership, operation and maintenance of the Storage Project. Essential Nature. The Fossil Station Owners hereby acknowledge that the right of the Storage Project to access and utilize the Common Facilities is essential to the storage, production and delivery of electric energy from the Storage Project to the CMP transmission facilities operated by ISO-NE. Vesting. The right to access and utilize the Common Facilities granted hereunder by the Fossil Station Owners to the Storage Project shall vest in Wyman as owner of the Storage Project and a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title, leasehold or other interest or rights in the Common Facilities. NATURE OF COMMON FACILITIES RIGHTS Nature of Services. The Fossil Station Owners shall provide certain services to the Storage Project consisting of those services the Fossil Station Owners receive through the CSIAs, as necessary to enable the energy generated by the Storage Project to reach the CMP transmission facilities operated by ISO-NE. The Parties acknowledge that the grant of rights under this Agreement by the Fossil Station Owners to Wyman on behalf of the Storage Project is made for the purpose of enabling the Storage Project to participate in the markets operated by the ISO-NE. Obligations of the Fossil Station Owners. The Fossil Station Owners shall exercise their rights and perform their obligations under this Agreement in a manner consistent with its obligations under the CSIAs. Obligations of Wyman on Behalf of the Storage Project. Wyman on behalf of the Storage Project shall exercise its rights and perform its obligations under this Agreement in a manner that is reasonable and facilitates the Fossil Station Owners’ performance under, and compliance with, the CSIAs. No Joint and Several Liability between the Fossil Station Owners and Wyman Acting on Behalf of the Storage Project. The Parties acknowledge that this Agreement does not subject the Fossil Station Owners to joint and several liability for any actions taken by Wyman on behalf of the Storage Project, and conversely does not subject the Storage Project to joint and several liability for any actions taken by the Parties on behalf of the Fossil Stations. Assignment or Transfer of Rights. Except as set forth in Section 9.6 hereof, Wyman and Wyman IV, respectively, shall not assign or transfer any rights granted to such Party hereunder with regard to the Common Facilities, or grant any permission, license, right of way or similar right with regard to the Common Facilities, without the prior written consent of the other Party which shall not be unreasonably delayed or denied. Interference. Subject to the terms of this Agreement, in no event shall Wyman on behalf of the Storage Project be entitled to exercise its rights to access and utilize the Common Facilities if the exercise of such rights would materially interfere with or limit the reasonable and necessary access and utilization of the Common Facilities by the Fossil Station Owners for purposes of operating and maintaining the Fossil Stations. MAINTENANCE OF COMMON FACILITIES Allocation of Certain Costs and Expenses. The Fossil Station Owners shall continue to be responsible for the operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of the Common Facilities (“Common O&M”). Costs and expenses incurred under the “Joint Ownership Agreement” by the Fossil Station Owners related to Common O&M (“Common O&M Expenses”) shall be allocated to the each respective Project on a pro rata basis using a ratio equal to the capacity of the Wyman Station, Wyman IV Station and Storage Project, respectively, divided by the combined capacity of the Projects, as such ratios may change from time to time to reflect current operating conditions of each Project. However, if there are any costs and expenses associated with the operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement of the Common Facilities that are solely attributable to the operation of Storage Project, such costs and expenses shall be borne solely by Storage (“Storage O&M Expenses”). Removal of Storage Project. Notwithstanding Section 4.1 above, in the event the Storage Project is removed and ceases use of the Common Facilities, or upon termination of this Agreement in the event the Fossil Station(s) continues to operate, Wyman shall be solely responsible for any costs incurred by the Fossil Station Owners in order to accomplish the removal of the Storage Project (“Removal Costs”). Successor Agreement. In the event that the Projects and the Common Facilities are no longer operated and maintained by the Parties for any reason, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate mutually agreeable terms and execute a mutually agreeable agreement (or amendment to this Agreement) that specifies the division of responsibilities of the entities providing operation and maintenance services associated with the Common Facilities. CHANGE IN LAW Change in Law. In the event that a change in the laws or regulations applicable to the Common Facilities requires the amendment, modification or replacement of this Agreement in order to satisfy any applicable federal, state or local regulatory requirements, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate and implement mutually agreeable terms to accomplish such amendment, modification or replacement. CERTAIN COVENANTS Authority and Operational Abilities. Each of the Parties represents, as of the Effective Date, and covenants for the term of this Agreement, that such Party has the legal authority and operational abilities to fulfill its obligations under this Agreement. Agreement to Cooperate. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Parties so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each Project benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Common Facilities as is necessary for the efficient operation of each such Project. Priority of Curtailment. For so long as the CMP-Wyman CSIA or the CMP-Wyman IV CSIA (the “CSIAs”) is in effect, and notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, in the event of curtailment pursuant to the CSIAs (or pursuant to applicable operating guides or applicable reliability standards and requirements), the Storage Project shall be curtailed as follows: first, and if necessary in full, any Project (if any) the operation of which is contributing to a ISO-NE system emergency; second, and if necessary in full, the Storage Project; and thereafter, the Fossil Stations. MATERIAL BREACH; LIMITATIONS Material Breach by any Party. In the event of any material breach of this Agreement by any Party and such Party fails to cure promptly such breach within a reasonable time, not to exceed sixty (60) days after receipt of written notice from the non-defaulting Party describing such breach, the non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, in addition to all remedies available to it at law or in equity, to: (i) cure the breach on behalf of the defaulting Party, or (ii) suspend the breaching Party’s access to all or any portion of the Common Facilities owned by such non-breaching Party for so long as such default shall be continuing and remain uncured. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event that a breach of this Agreement could give rise to a breach by Wyman or Wyman IV pursuant to the terms of the applicable CSIAs, the non-defaulting Party shall not be required to provide the defaulting Party with notice and/or an opportunity to cure in order to exercise the remedies specified in clause (i) or (ii) above; provided, that the remedy specified in clause (i) may be exercised, without prejudice to any right or remedy of any Party hereunder, by any lender of such Party. If a Party (or any lender thereof) chooses to cure a Party’s default, the defaulting Party shall reimburse the non-defaulting Party (or such Party’s lender) upon demand for all commercially reasonable costs incurred by the non-defaulting Party (or such Party’s lender) in curing such default. Except for indemnification obligations related to third-party claims as provided for in Section 9.7, in no event shall any Party be liable under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages including, but not limited to, loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability. FORCE MAJEURE Force Majeure. In the event of an act of God, government order or restraint, war (declared or undeclared) or warlike conditions, act of terrorism, blockade, revolution, strike, lockout, civil commotion, fire, flood, storm, epidemic or any other occurrence beyond a Party’s reasonable control (each a “Force Majeure Event”), such Party shall promptly notify each other Party thereof and, so long as such condition shall persist, such Party shall not be liable for the delay in performance of, or the failure to perform, its obligations (other than obligations for payment of amounts due hereunder) under this Agreement caused directly or indirectly thereby. The claiming Party shall give each other Party notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event. Within fifteen (15) days after giving notice of the Force Majeure Event, the claiming Party shall give each other Party an estimate of the Force Majeure Event’s expected duration and probable impact. The claiming Party shall continue to furnish each other Party with timely regular reports during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event. Each Party shall promptly exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit the impact to its obligations hereunder as a result of the Force Majeure Event. MISCELLANEOUS Relationship of Parties. The Parties do not intend to create hereby any joint venture, partnership, association or any other entity for the conduct of any business. Except as provided in Section 7.1, nothing herein shall be deemed to authorize any Party to act on behalf of any other Party. Non-Interference. Each Party agrees not to interfere with the reasonable and necessary utilization of the Common Facilities by any other Party as permitted hereunder. Modification and Amendment. The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all of the Parties. Waiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party’s right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights, and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect. Enforceability. Any provision of this Agreement which is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. Assignment. No Party may assign any of its benefits, rights or obligations hereunder to any third party without the prior written consent of each other Party, provided, however, that any Party may collaterally assign its interests in this Agreement to any lender in connection with a financing or a refinancing of its respective Project. Indemnification. Each Party shall indemnify, defend and hold each other Party, its officers, directors, shareholders, members and affiliates, harmless from any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demand, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting from the indemnifying Party’s performance or non-performance of its obligations under this Agreement, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing, by the indemnified Party. Choice of Law, Jurisdiction and Waiver of Jury Trial. (i) This Agreement and the rights and obligations of the Parties hereunder will be governed pursuant to, and enforced, construed and interpreted in accordance with, the laws of Maine without regard to principles of conflicts of laws.
(ii) Each of the Parties irrevocably and unconditionally submits to the exclusive jurisdiction of the United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida for the purposes of any suit, action or other proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the transactions contemplated hereby, any provision hereof or the breach, performance, enforcement or validity or invalidity of this Agreement or any provision hereof (and agrees not to commence any suit, action or proceeding relating thereto except in such courts). (iii) THE PARTIES HERETO EACH HEREBY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVE THE RIGHT EACH MAY HAVE TO A TRIAL BY JURY WITH RESPECT TO ANY PROCEEDINGS BASED HEREON, OR ARISING OUT OF, UNDER OR IN CONNECTION WITH THIS AGREEMENT, OR ANY COURSE OF CONDUCT, COURSE OF DEALING, STATEMENTS (WHETHER ORAL OR WRITTEN) OR ACTIONS OF ANY PARTY TO THIS AGREEMENT. THIS PROVISION IS A MATERIAL INDUCEMENT FOR THE PARTIES TO ENTER INTO THIS AGREEMENT. Inspection of Records. Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the Common Facilities held by any other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times. Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement of the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof. Section Headings. The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof. Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument. Specific Performance. The Parties hereto may demand specific performance of this Agreement. Each Party hereby irrevocably waives any defense based on the adequacy of a remedy at law and any other defense which might be asserted to bar the remedy of specific performance.
